{
  "doc_id": "21909",
  "text": "The initial exposure to food allergens occurs predominantly via the gastrointestinal tract or skin. An impaired skin barrier could lead to increased transcutaneous passage of antigens and subsequent sensitization. An association between the early onset of AD and development of FA has been shown [CITATION_1] . In the gastrointestinal tract, the two main factors influencing immune tolerance are dietary factors and microbiota composition and function [CITATION_2] . Kim et al. demonstrated that under normal physiological conditions, macromolecules from the diet induce the bulk of regulatory T cells (Tregs) development, which is essential for suppressing a default immune response to dietary antigens [CITATION_3] . Observational studies have suggested that the early introduction of peanut [CITATION_4] , egg [CITATION_5] , or cow's milk [CITATION_6] may prevent the development of allergy to these foods. A randomized controlled trial (Learning Early about Peanut Allergy, LEAP) showed that the early consumption of peanut in high-risk infants with severe eczema, egg allergy, or both reduced the development of peanut allergy by 80% by 5 years of age [CITATION_7] . The Persistence of Oral Tolerance to Peanut (LEAP-On) study showed that the absence of reactivity is maintained in these subjects [CITATION_8] .",
